This case has not been concluded. Unless a judgment of conviction is entered, the defendant is presumed innocent of all charges.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

2:15 PM Call to Order by Court.  Appearances stated: Defendant Ariel A. Tiderman not in court.  Attorney Steven W. Zaleski appeared by video for Ariel A. Tiderman.  Attorney Luke Steiner appeared by video for State of Wisconsin. 

Attorney Zaleski is heard on non appearance. Received an offer. Attorney Zaleski has not been able to get in touch with client. 

Court issues a warrant defendant to be held for bond hearing.

10:34 AM Call to Order by Court.  Appearances stated: Defendant Ariel A. Tiderman appeared by phone.  Attorney Steven W. Zaleski appeared by video for Ariel A. Tiderman.  Attorney Luke Steiner appeared by video for State of Wisconsin. 

Attorney Zaleski is heard, they're ready to proceed with the preliminary hearing.

1W - Deputy Berg, sworn. 
Exam by Attorney Steiner.
Cross by Attorney Zaleski. 
Objection by Attorney Steiner.
Withdrawn by Attorney Zaleski. 

State requests matter to be bound over for further proceedings.

Court finds probable cause and binds matter over for further proceedings.  

Attorney Zaleski is ready to proceed with arraignment. 
10:45 AM Information filed. 

Attorney Zaleski is heard waives reading of the information. Defendant will stand mute, upon defendant standing mute clerk will enter a not guilty plea into the record as to each count.

Jury status hearing on September 29, 2022 at 02:00 pm.
